1. Network Protocols: Full Forms & Uses
-> HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol): Used to transfer data (like text and images) over the web, though it sends data in plain text without encryption.

-> HTTPS (Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure): The secure version of HTTP that encrypts data transfers to protect sensitive information like passwords or credit cards.

-> FTP (File Transfer Protocol): Used specifically for uploading, downloading, and transferring files between a client and a server over a network.

-> SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol): The standard protocol used for sending and routing emails from an email client to a mail server.

2. IPv4 vs. IPv6
-> IPv4 uses a 32-bit numerical address format (e.g., 192.168.1.1) providing roughly 4.3 billion unique addresses, which the world has mostly run out of. IPv6 uses a 128-bit hexadecimal format (e.g., 2001:db8::ff00:42:8329), providing a virtually infinite number of unique addresses to accommodate all modern internet-connected devices.

