4. HTTP Status Codes Explained
-> (200) OK: The request was successful, and the server delivered the expected data.

-> (301) Moved Permanently: The requested URL has been permanently assigned a new address, and the browser should redirect there.

-> (403) Forbidden: The server understands your request, but you do not have permission or authorization to access the resource.

-> (404) Not Found: The server cannot find the requested webpage or file; it either doesn’t exist or the URL was mistyped.

-> (500) Internal Server Error: A generic error message meaning something went wrong on the website's server side, preventing it from fulfilling the request.

5. DNS Hierarchy Explained
-> The Domain Name System (DNS) is organized like an inverted tree structure, reading from right to left to resolve an address. Here is how it breaks down using www.google.com (which technically ends with an invisible trailing dot www.google.com.):

-> Root Level (.): The absolute top of the hierarchy. It doesn't have a name (represented by an empty string or the hidden dot at the very end) and directs requests to the correct Top-Level Domain (TLD) registry.

-> TLD (Top-Level Domain) (.com): The next layer down, managed by specific registries. Common examples include .com, .org, or country codes like .in.

-> Domain / Second-Level Domain (google): The unique name registered by an individual or organization under a specific TLD. In this case, google is the domain name.

-> Subdomain (www): A subsection created under the main domain to organize different services. Here, www is a subdomain pointing to their primary web server (other examples could be maps.google.com or mail.google.com).
